About the Company

Urka Sren and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products.Sren used her background as an artist to develop technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits. Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.

1. Business Task

The business task is to analyze Bellabeat user behavior and engagement patterns to identify trends and areas of improvement. The ultimate goal is to use this knowledge to develop new products and services that better meet the needs and expectations of the target audience, ultimately driving growth and increasing revenue for the brand. Business recommendations will be delivered to the stakeholders Urka Sren, Sando Mur, and the Bellabeat marketing analytics team by the conclusion of the project.

2. Prepare the Data

  • The data can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit where the data is stored in 18 CSV files

  • The data is limited in several ways, such as It is from the year 2016 The timeframe is a short duration of 2 months Tthe demographics of the users is unspecfic It is a small sampling size which varis from 33 to 8 throughout the various csv files All of the the factors listed reduces the statistical power of the analysis, which can distort the validity of the results

  • The data is available on Kaggle publicly, FitBit Fitness Tracker Data with a (CC0: Public Domain) liscense

Date formatting

After viewing the datasets with skim_without_charts and View functions I noticed the Date format was Chr and not date like I wanted so I changed the format to Date

sleepDay$new_date <- mdy_hms(sleepDay$sleep_day)

Because the data is missing values I viewed the mean and median values from the summary chart to determine the best way to visualize each data case & possible relationships between the different variables.

The highest time of activity was inactivity and second was light activity, leading me to believe most users spend the most of their activity time partaking in light activity

Getting people to go further thus for spending more time can lead to getting more people to go further and spend more lightly active time. The users that go the shortest distances with light activity also maintain the level and do so consistently daily.

The more steps and the further the distances people make the more calories get burned. As seen in this chart the number of steps taken doesnt necessarily mean more calories get burned, even when the outliers are uncounted for.

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Most users average around 8hours of sleep and start light activity when they wake up.

4.1 Summary of Analysis:

It appears people go the furthest distance while very active but the consistency at which they do so is inconsistent. moderate and light activity tends to trend at a consistent distance on a daily basis. *Light activity is also the 2nd highest form of activity recorded, which begins when people wake up and before the go to bed. The more steps and the further the distances people make the more calories get burned.

5. Final conclusion:

The highest time of activity was inactivity and second was light activity, leading me to believe most users spend most of their activity time partaking in light activity. The number of steps taken doesnt necessarily mean more calories get burned. I think its realistic to assume moderate and light activity that burns calories effectively is something to encourage & will appeal to the average users of the fitbit.
